Claims WHAT IS CLAIMED IS: 1. An aptamer that binds to alpha-synuclein protein, comprising: a) a nucleic acid comprising or consisting of any one of a-syn-1 (SEQ ID NO: 1), a-syn-2(SEQ ID NO: 2), a-syn-3(SEQ ID NO: 3), a-syn-4(SEQ ID NO: 4), or a-syn-5(SEQ ID NO: 5); b) a nucleic acid having at least 70% sequence identity to the nucleic acid sequence of a); c) a nucleic acid that hybridizes with the complementary strand of the nucleic acid of a); d) a nucleic acid that differs from a) by one or more nucleotides that are substituted, deleted, and/or inserted; or e) a derivative of a), b), c), or d). 2. The aptamer of claim 1 , wherein in step (b) said nucleic acid has at least 70%, 71 %, 72%, 73%, 74%, 75%, 76%, 77%, 78%, 79%, 80%, 81 %, 82%, 83%, 84%, 85%, 86%, 87%, 88%, 89%, 90%, 91 %, 92%, 93%, 94%, 95%, 96%, 97%, 98%, or 99% sequence identity. 3. The aptamer of claim 1 , wherein in step (c) said nucleic acid hybridizes with the complementary strand of the nucleic acid of a) under conditions of high stringency. 4. A method for producing a nucleic acid aptamer, comprising: (a) a complex formation step of mixing a single-stranded nucleic acid library with alpha- synuclein protein monomers in a solution to form a complex of a single-stranded nucleic acid and the alpha-synuclein protein monomers, (b) an aggregation step to promote aggregation of alpha-synuclein monomers to larger order aggregates such as fibrils, (c) a recovery step of recovering the complex from the solution; (d) an amplification step of recovering the single-stranded nucleic acid from the complex and then amplifying the single-stranded nucleic acid by a nucleic acid amplification method; 

 (e) and a single-stranded nucleic acid preparation step of converting the double- stranded nucleic acids obtained in the amplification step into single strands and then forming an intramolecular conformation. 5. The method of claim 4, wherein said recovery step comprises a size selection step. 6. The method of claim 4 or 5, wherein said recovery step comprises an ultracentrifugation step. 7. A liposome comprising, one or more lipids, and at least one aptamer of any one of claims 1 to 3. 8. The liposome of claim 7, further comprising a targeting moiety. 9. The liposomes of claim 8, wherein said targeting moiety is a transferrin receptor aptamer. 10. A method of treating a subject having, or suspected of having, a neurodegenerative disease, comprising: administering at least one aptamer of any one of claims 1 to 3. 11. A method of treating a subject having, or suspected of having, a neurodegenerative disease, comprising: administering a pharmaceutical composition comprising at least one aptamer of any one of claims 1 to 3, and a pharmaceutically acceptable carrier. 12. The method of claim 10 or 1 1 , wherein said neurodegenerative disease is Parkinson's disease (PD), dementia with Lewy bodies (DLB), or multiple system atrophy (MSA). 13. The method of any one of claims 10 to 12, wherein said subject is a human. 14. A method of treating a subject having, or suspected of having, a neurodegenerative disease, comprising: administering a liposome comprising at least one aptamer of any one of claims 1 to 3, and optionally comprising a pharmaceutically acceptable carrier. 15. The method of claim 14, wherein said liposome further comprising a targeting moiety. 16. The method of claim 15, wherein said targeting moiety is a transferrin receptor aptamer. 17. The method of any one of claims 14 to 16, wherein said neurodegenerative disease is Parkinson's disease (PD), dementia with Lewy bodies (DLB), or multiple system atrophy (MSA). 18. The method of anyone of claims 14 to 17, wherein said subject is a human. 19. Use of an aptamer of any one of claims 1 to 3, for treating a subject having, or suspected of having, a neurodegenerative disease. 20. Use of an aptamer of any one of claims 1 to 3, in the manufacture of a medicament for treating a subject having, or suspected of having, a neurodegenerative disease. 21. Use of a pharmaceutical composition comprising at least one aptamer of any one of claims 1 to 3, and a pharmaceutically acceptable carrier, for treating a subject having, or suspected of having, a neurodegenerative disease. 22. Use of a pharmaceutical composition comprising at least one aptamer of any one of claims 1 to 3, and a pharmaceutically acceptable carrier, in the manufacture of a medicament for treating a subject having, or suspected of having, a neurodegenerative disease. 23. The use of any one of claims 19 to 22, wherein said neurodegenerative disease is Parkinson's disease (PD), dementia with Lewy bodies (DLB), or multiple system atrophy (MSA). 24. The method of any one of claims 19 to 23, wherein said subject is a human. 25. Use of a liposome comprising at least aptamer of any one of claims 1 to 3, and optionally a pharmaceutically acceptable carrier, for treating a subject having, or suspected of having, a neurodegenerative disease . 26. Use of a liposome comprising at least one aptamer of any one of claims 1 to 3, and optionally a pharmaceutically acceptable carrier, in the manufacture of a medicament for treating a subject having, or suspected of having, a neurodegenerative disease. 27. The use of claim 25 or 26, wherein said liposome further comprising a targeting moiety. 28. The use of any one of claims 25 to 27, wherein said targeting moiety is a transferrin receptor aptamer. 29. The use of any one of claims 25 to 28, wherein said neurodegenerative disease is Parkinson's disease (PD), dementia with Lewy bodies (DLB), or multiple system atrophy (MSA). 30. The use of anyone of claims 25 to 29, wherein said subject is a human. 31. A method for detecting alpha-synuclein polypeptide in a biological sample, comprising: contacting said sample with an aptamer of any one of claims 1 to 3, said aptamer comprising a detectable label, and determining whether an increase in fluorescence occurs, wherein an increase in fluorescence is indicative of the presence of alpha-synuclein polypeptide in the sample. 32. A kit comprising one or more aptamers that binds to alpha-synuclein protein, comprising: a) a nucleic acid comprising or consisting of any one of a-syn-1 (SEQ ID NO: 1), a-syn-2(SEQ ID NO: 2), a-syn-3(SEQ ID NO: 3), a-syn-4(SEQ ID NO: 4), or a-syn-5(SEQ ID NO: 5); b) a nucleic acid having at least 70% sequence identity to the nucleic acid sequence of a); 

 c) a nucleic acid that hybridizes with the complementary strand of the nucleic acid of a); d) a nucleic acid that differs from a) by one or more nucleotides that are substituted, deleted, and/or inserted; or e) a derivative of a), b), c), or d), and optionally instructions. 33. The kit of claim 32, comprising one or more aptamers selected from SEQ ID NO: 1 , SEQ ID NO: 2, SEQ ID NO: 3, SEQ ID NO: 4, SEQ ID NO:5. 34. The kit of claim 32 or 33, further comprising a detectable label. 35. The kit of any one of claims 32 to 34, further comprising a targeting moiety. 36. The kit of any one of claims 32 to 35, further comprising a transferrin receptor aptamer. 37. The kit of any one of claims 32 to 36, further comprising a neutral lipid, an anionic lipid, a cationic lipid, or a zwitterionic lipid.
